<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-29T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-29T09:00:00-05:00" n="314" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">860D.6359 International Nickel Co./10:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-29T16:00:00+02:00">July 29,
                                    1940—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received July 29—3:03 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>328. The Minister of Foreign Affairs told me today that directors of the
                            Petsamo Nickel Company had now agreed to deliver nickel ore <pb facs="0347" n="335" xml:id="pg_335"/> from their mines to the
                            Germans and the Russians until the end of the current year in the
                            proportion of 60 and 40 percent respectively. While this arrangement was
                            not palatable to the British Government it had acquiesced.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>